    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1807_08_02_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <note>9</note>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                        <date when="1807-08-02">Aug<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1807.</date></dateline></opener>
                  
            <p>
                As my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father's</persName> secretary I have just<lb/>
                received a commission, which I execute<lb/>
                with much pleasure. He commissions<lb/>
                me, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir,</persName> to say, that if you could be <choice><orig>pre-<lb/>
                vailed</orig><reg>prevailed</reg></choice> upon to come to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland,</placeName> to spend<lb/>
                some months in this family, he would<lb/>
                use his utmost endeavors to make<lb/>
                your time pass agreeably, &amp;, as it is your<lb/>
                wish to know something of the manners<lb/>
                of the lower classes of the people of this <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">country,</placeName><lb/>
                he may add, not unprofitably. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. <choice><orig>Edge-<lb/>
                worth</orig><reg>Edgeworth</reg></choice></persName> joins in the same hopes, and <choice><orig>as-<lb/>
                -sures</orig><reg>assures</reg></choice> you, that you should have an <choice><orig>a-<lb/>
                -partment</orig><reg>apartment</reg></choice> in which you could enjoy<lb/>
                learned leisure at any hour when you<lb/>
                might wish to retire from our family<lb/>
                society. You would not be tormented<lb/>
                with idle visitors, as we endeavor to <choice><orig>cul-<lb/>
                -tivate</orig><reg>cultivate</reg></choice> friendship, and not acquaintance.<lb/>
                
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1807_08_02_page02.jpg"/>
                My brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> tells us, that you are<lb/>
                occupied in some literary work, at which<lb/>
                we rejoice, for the sake of the public, and<lb/>
                for our own. Your visit to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"><choice><orig>Edgeworth's<lb/>
                -town</orig><reg>Edgeworthstown</reg></choice></placeName> would not delay this work; because<lb/>
                you could in this retired place, go on<lb/>
                with it perhaps better than in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London.</placeName><lb/>
                My father is also engaged in a work on<lb/>
                education; and your conversations<lb/>
                on literary subjects would be mutually<lb/>
                advantageous and agreeable. Permit<lb/>
                me to express my own anxious wishes<lb/>
                to profit by them.<lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                 We are truly obliged to you, Sir, for your<lb/>
                 kindness to my brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd,</persName> and he<lb/>
                 is fully sensible of the value of your<lb/>
                 approbation, and regard.<lb/></p>
                <closer>
                 I am with much respect<lb/>
                 Your obliged Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.<lb/>
                 <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth.</persName><lb/> </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
